  "slug": "albondigas-en-salsa",
  "title": "Albóndigas en salsa",
  "subtitle": "Spanish meatballs in tomato sauce",
  "excerpt": "Pork and beef meatballs simmered in a smoky tomato sauce with paprika, bay, and a splash of wine. The Spanish version of a dish that appears across Southern Europe, more paprika, less tomato than the Italian equivalent. Serves four.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Albóndigas en salsa is one of the classic tapas and main-course dishes of Spain, with regional variations across Catalonia, Andalusia, and Castile. Documented by Penelope Casas in Tapas: The Little Dishes of Spain (1985) and Claudia Roden in The Food of Spain (2011). The sauce typically uses smoked paprika and sometimes a splash of dry sherry or white wine.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The key to albóndigas that hold together is keeping the mix cold before rolling and not overworking the meat. Warm hands break down the fat in the mince, which makes the meatballs dense and prone to falling apart in the sauce. Mix quickly, refrigerate for 15 minutes if the kitchen is warm, then roll fast.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The sauce here is built on onion, smoked paprika, and tinned tomatoes, simpler than a long-cooked ragù, thicker and more paprika-forward than most Italian tomato sauces. The meatballs finish cooking in the sauce, which flavours both components as they simmer together.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
