      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make and fry the meatballs",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Combine {{pork-mince}} of pork mince and {{beef-mince}} of beef mince in a large bowl with {{garlic}} of grated garlic, {{breadcrumbs-dried}} of breadcrumbs, the beaten egg, {{parsley-flat}} of chopped parsley, {{sea-salt-fine}} of salt, and {{black-pepper}} of black pepper. Mix briefly with your hands until just combined, overworking makes the meatballs dense. Roll into balls about 3 cm across. Heat {{olive-oil}} of olive oil in a wide saucepan over medium-high heat. Brown the meatballs in batches, turning so they colour on all sides, about 3 to 4 minutes per batch. Remove and set aside.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make the sauce and finish",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "In the same pan, add {{olive-oil}} of olive oil and cook {{onion}} finely chopped onion over medium heat for 8 minutes until soft. Add {{garlic}} of garlic and {{tomato-puree}} of tomato purée; cook for 1 minute. Add {{paprika-smoked}} of smoked paprika and stir for 30 seconds. Pour in the wine if using and let it bubble until absorbed. Add {{tinned-tomatoes}} of hand-crushed tomatoes, {{bay-leaves}} bay leaves, and {{sea-salt-fine}} of salt. Simmer for 10 minutes. Return the meatballs to the pan, nestling them into the sauce. Cover and simmer for 15 minutes until cooked through. Remove the bay leaves and serve.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "intro": null,
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Make sure the egg and breadcrumbs are well distributed before rolling. Brown the meatballs fully before they go into the sauce, the crust holds them together.",
              "cause": "Mix not bound enough, or meatballs not browned first to form a crust.",
              "symptom": "Meatballs falling apart in the sauce"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Mix only until combined. The meatballs need 15 minutes simmering in sauce, not longer.",
              "cause": "Meat overworked when mixing, or cooked too long.",
              "symptom": "Meatballs dry and dense"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Simmer the sauce for at least 10 minutes before adding the meatballs. If still sharp, add a pinch of sugar.",
              "cause": "Tomatoes not cooked long enough to lose their rawness.",
              "symptom": "Sauce too acidic"
            }
          ],
          "heading": "Common problems"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Albóndigas appear across the Spanish-speaking world, from the tapas bars of Madrid to the home cooking of Mexico, where the sauce changes character entirely. In Spain the dish is served as a tapa in small portions or as a main course with bread and wine. The smoked paprika in the sauce marks it as Spanish rather than Italian; the combination of pork and beef in the mix gives a richer flavour than either mince alone. It is the kind of dish that is better the second day, once the meatballs have had time to absorb the sauce.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
